<P N="50">L. A gentleman of fortune will be o&s;ten complaining of taxes&punc; that his e&s;tate is incon&s;iderable; that he can never make &s;o much of it as the world is ready to imagine. A mere citizen, $n the other hand, is always aiming to &s;hew his riches; &s;ays that he employs &s;o many hands; he keeps his wife a chai&s;e and one; and talks much of his Chine&s;e ornaments at his pal$ry cake-hou&s;e in the coun|try.
